[2] UK (England)
Date: Tue 25 May 2017 14:59
Source: Gloucestershire Live [edited]
http://www.gloucestershirelive.co.uk/news/gloucester-news/cases-measles-rise-south-west-75570


There were almost 100 cases of measles recorded in the South West [of England] last year [2016] - the highest total since the last outbreak in 2013.

The region recorded just 13 measles cases in 2015, but that figure rocketed to 96 in 2016 - making it the 2nd highest region outside London.

Last year's total was not as high as in 2013, when there were 163 which was the 2nd-highest on record in data going back to 1996.

Measles causes fever, a rash, conjunctivitis and can cause serious complications and even death.

Only 7 of the 96 measles cases last year [2016] were in Gloucestershire according to county council stats.

But parents have still been warned to make sure their children are vaccinated from the illness. Across the South West, 92.9 percent of children in 2015/16 were given their 1st dose of the vaccine against measles by their 2nd birthday.

[Byline: Matt Discombe]

